    <title>Combined summary - A proposal for up-front payments.</title>
    <updated>2023-06-02T21:25:37.157460+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2019-November/002343.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Lightning Network community is actively discussing proposals to prevent spamming on the network. One proposal involves requiring a fee or implementing proof-of-work incentives, while others suggest upfront payments or prepaid HTLCs. However, concerns about privacy and power concentration in the hands of big actors have been raised.There have also been discussions around the onion routing protocol used in Bitcoin's Lightning Network to maintain privacy and prevent spam. Concerns about failure resulting in loss of funds and payment scheme structures have been highlighted.Other proposals include rate limits for trusted and untrusted nodes, building a reputation-based system, and solving PoW puzzles to prevent spam. The discussions have revolved around finding ways to prevent spam and maintain privacy in the Lightning Network.In addition, the Lightning Network team has discussed reversing the direction of bond payments, charging an up-front fee for accepting any HTLC, and implementing different rate limits for failures to isolate spammers. Rusty Russell has proposed a solution to avoid Type 2 spam by implementing up-front payments for messages.Further discussions involved fair pricing formulae, prepayment hashes to generate nonces, and the issue of routing failure and refunds. There were suggestions of using ECC trapdoor and scriptless scripts to prevent uncooperative routing failure cases.Overall, the discussions aim to create a distributed system that cannot be censored and strike a balance between decentralization and censorship-resistance while considering potential impacts on power dynamics.</summary>
